(1736, 1, '2015-03-23 20:18:10', '2015-03-23 20:18:10', '<h2>Objective</h2>\r\nChoosing any topic and any design style, create an informational site.\r\n<h2>Implementation</h2>\r\nI''d been seeing a lot of single-page long-scrolling sites being used for start-ups, designers, <a href="http://www.spelltower.com/" target="_blank">products</a>... etc. and thought it would be a good fit. My wife was 7 months pregnant at the time, so we were talking a lot about education, and how we wanted to raise our child, so the topic of immersion education was an easy choice.\r\n\r\nFrom a design side, I wanted to work with bold colors. I naturally am pretty conservative with colors, so I wanted to stretch myself that way.\r\n\r\nI chose a system where each section of content would have its own color background, and re-used those colors for the text and graphics of the other sections to create some consistency and uniformity when the backgrounds are so different.\r\n\r\nFrom a coding standpoint, it''s a very simple site. Just one page with jump links on an nav fixed to the top of the page. I did learn how to create the full-width element with a nested centered element, which was very satisfying.\r\n<h2>What I would do differently now</h2>\r\nIt''s a static site, so I would make it responsive. I would also take a look at the nav and see if it makes more sense somewhere else. I think it''s a little distracting on the top. Also given it''s strctural simplicity, I could look at beefing up the content and adding more interactive elements like animations.', 'Long-scrolling informational site', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'long-scrolling-informational-site', '', '', '2015-04-18 02:17:45', '2015-04-18 02:17:45', '', 0, 'http://localhost/fn/?post_type=project&#038;p=1736', 0, 'project', '', 0),
(1737, 1, '2015-03-23 20:17:38', '2015-03-23 20:17:38', '', 'webdesign1_480', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'webdesign1_480', '', '', '2015-03-23 20:17:38', '2015-03-23 20:17:38', '', 1736, 'http://localhost/fn/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/webdesign1_480.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(1738, 1, '2015-03-23 20:20:15', '2015-03-23 20:20:15', '<h2>Objective</h2>\r\nTo build a plug-in tool with javascript that could be used on a site we were working on. Since I was working on a responsive site, I chose to build a tool to create a pop-up window the size of a different device so you could see how the layout looked at that size.\r\n<h2>Implementation</h2>\r\nI used <a href="http://fortawesome.github.io/Font-Awesome/icons/" target="_blank">FontAwesome icons</a> to represent the device sizes, and jQuery to create the hide/show effect on the menu.\r\n\r\nIt took a lot of trial and error to come to get the device withs and sizes working properly, but the code itself is pretty simple:\r\n<pre><code>openNewWindow: function(){ //new window features, size, options...etc //35px added to width to accomodate scroll bar and outer border of window var newPop; var currentURL= window.location.href; var maxW = screen.width; var maxH = screen.height; var newWinSpecs = "scrollbars=yes,status=yes,height=1,width=1";  $(''#desktop'').click (function(){ if(window.isPopup===undefined){ console.log("you just clicked on the desktop!"); newPop = window.open(currentURL, "", newWinSpecs); newPop.resizeTo(maxW, maxH); newPop.isPopup = true; } else{ window.resizeTo(maxW, maxH); } }); </code></pre>\r\nIt was really satisfying when the I got the tool to work properly. Javascript was really challenging to learn bacause I had been so used to how concrete HTML and CSS are as languages. The abstract nature of javascript was hard to adjust to, but I recognize how much power it has. I''m looking forward to learning more.', 'Javascript plug-in for testing responsive designs', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'javascript-plug-in-for-testing-responsive-designs', '', '', '2015-04-18 02:14:50', '2015-04-18 02:14:50', '', 0, 'http://localhost/fn/?post_type=project&#038;p=1738', 0, 'project', '', 0),
(1739, 1, '2015-03-23 20:19:53', '2015-03-23 20:19:53', '', 'webdev2_240', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'webdev2_240', '', '', '2015-03-23 20:19:53', '2015-03-23 20:19:53', '', 1738, 'http://localhost/fn/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/webdev2_240.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(1740, 1, '2015-03-23 20:24:14', '2015-03-23 20:24:14', '<h2>Objective</h2>\r\nUsing an existing responsive grid system, build a four-page responsive site dedicated to a public service, with each page having a different layout.\r\n<h2>Implementation</h2>\r\nI chose <a href="http://www.getskeleton.com/" target="_blank">Skeleton</a> as my grid system. Skeleton uses up to 16 columns, but I used 12. This allowed me to use 6, 4, and 3-column layouts to differentiate each page.\r\n\r\nThe header, footer, nav and image/video clear all the columns on each page, creating consistency in the layout while the number of column change. The footer and nav are set to cover the full width of the browser window. This makes the layout feel like it''s part of the larger viewing area, even though it''s centered horizontally.\r\n\r\nI used a couple different methods to accomplish the responsive aspect of the design, but primarily I used the<code>float:left</code> style and then manipulated the widths of the columns so they would sit next to each other and then stack on top of each other as the viewing portal gets smaller:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://localhost/fn/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/webdesign2_3.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-1741" src="http://localhost/fn/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/webdesign2_3-300x154.png" alt="webdesign2_3" width="300" height="154" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://localhost/fn/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/webdesign2_4.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-1742" src="http://localhost/fn/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/webdesign2_4-191x300.png" alt="webdesign2_4" width="191" height="300" /></a>', 'Responsive informational site', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'responsive-informational-site', '', '', '2015-04-18 02:18:45', '2015-04-18 02:18:45', '', 0, 'http://localhost/fn/?post_type=project&#038;p=1740', 0, 'project', '', 0),
